Analysis Question

In this report, we seek to understand a dataset of patients with certain heart and physical health conditions. The aim is to build a model for the response maxhr (maximum heart rate attained during exericse) based on the physical conditions of the participants. The data is obtained from Machine Learning Repository @ UCI.

Data Processing

Observe that besides the binary categorical variables, we need to convert the other categorical variables with more than 2 levels into factor variables.

Regression & Model Selection

Focus on the plot of maxhr with all other covariates.

plot(maxhr ~., data=heart, cex=0.5)

From the correlation matrix, note that there are certain variables that are correlated with maxhr: age = -0.3938, chestpain = -0.3344, exang = -0.37, oldpeak = -0.343, slope = 0.386.

Other covariates, such as sex, restecg and restbp have a low correlation with maxhr. However, given the possibility of 2-way interaction of these covariates with other covariates in explaining maxhr, I will not discard these variables, and leave them in for now.

Stepwise Backward Selection

With 12 covariates, I will perform backward stepwise selection, using both AIC and BIC as the criterion, and in my initial model, I will consider up to 2-ways interaction.

At every point, we will find the AIC/BIC of all models if a particular covariate or interaction is dropped. Then, we will drop the covariate that gives the lowest AIC/BIC if it was dropped. The stopping criterion is only when the existing model has the lowest AIC/BIC compared to if we drop any other covariate and/or interaction. The difference between AIC and BIC is: \[BIC = nlog(RSS/n) + plog(n)\] \[AIC = nlog(RSS/n) + 2p\] The difference between AIC and BIC is that in the penalization for a complex model with large p, the scaling constant is log(n) - the larger n is, the more larger covariates will be penalized, while for AIC, it is only the constant = 2. AIC will choose a larger model than BIC, but BIC penalizes model complexity more severely.

I will obtain the model based on both AIC and BIC as stopping criterion. Since the steps are really long, to save space, I have commented out the code, and only pasted the first, and last 2 steps below.

model.one.max = lm(maxhr ~ (age+sex+chestpain+restbp+restecg+exang+oldpeak+
                       slope+fluoro+extest+fbs+chol)**2, data=heart)

Obviously, the BIC chooses a much smaller model than AIC. Which is preferred?

Cross Validation

To ensure that predictions will be accurate, let us perform a cross validation as well on the AIC and BIC model, and verify that AIC gives a better prediction. I will split the dataset into 3/4 (training) and 1/4 (test). We will run the model on training set to find the coefficients, but the variables selected will be the the selected variables by AIC and BIC stepwise, with the splitting into test and train set different. Repeat the simulation for 100 times, and find the mean of the MSE for each model size.

mse.function <- function (actual,pred) {
  sqrt(mean((actual - pred)^2))
}

aic.mse = rep(0, 100)
bic.mse = rep(0, 100)

for (i in 1:100) {
  set.seed(i*2)
  sample = sample(nrow(heart), size=(3/4)*nrow(heart), replace=F)
  train.set1 = heart[sample,]
  test.set1 = heart[-sample,]

  aic.test1 = lm(maxhr ~ age + sex + chestpain + restbp + restecg + exang + slope + 
       fluoro + extest + fbs + chol + age:chestpain + age:fluoro + 
       age:extest + sex:exang + sex:fluoro + sex:extest + sex:fbs + 
      chestpain:restbp + chestpain:slope + restbp:extest + restbp:chol + 
      restecg:slope + fluoro:extest, data = train.set1)
  aic.predict1 = predict(aic.test1, newdata=test.set1)
  aic.mse[i] = mse.function(test.set1$maxhr, aic.predict1)

  bic.test1 = lm(maxhr ~ age + sex + exang + slope + sex:exang, data = train.set1)
  bic.predict1 = predict(bic.test1, newdata=test.set1)
  bic.mse[i] = mse.function(test.set1$maxhr, bic.predict1)
}
mean(aic.mse)
## [1] 18.47
mean(bic.mse)
## [1] 18.29

Interestingly, the BIC performs slightly better.

In my opinion, the optimal model will be one that has a number of coefficients in between the optimal one chosen by AIC and BIC. Since it is easier to work downwards (remove variables from a larger model) than to work upwards (adding remaining p - q variables to a model with q variable), it also accounts for why we chose to work with the AIC-selected model instead of the BIC-selected model to find the final model that is a conpromise of both.

Reducing the Model

Using the AIC model, we ask ourselves, can it be reduced even further? A concern is that under a predictive model, we should also ensure the model do not get too overwhelming complex. Currently, our model contains 11/12 variables that the data presents, which may lead to some concerns of overfitting.

Based on the coefficients, we will find several reduced models, and use the F-Test to determine if the reduced model is sufficient.

Recall that for the F-Test to investigate if a reduced model is sufficient, we require \[F = \frac{(RSS_\omega - RSS_\lambda)/(p-q)}{RSS_\lambda/(n-p)} \sim F_{p-q,n-p}\]

Where \(\omega\) is the reduced model, \(\lambda\) is the full model, p is the number of variables in the full model, and q is the number of variables in the reduced model. Recall the null hypothesis is that the reduced model performs as well as the full model.

Because of the model hierachy, we face the following problems:

  1. If we remove a one-way variable, we have to remove all its interaction terms too.

  2. We either keep all levels of a factor variable, or remove all of them.

We explored a few models, but the more significant ones are presented below.

Hence, we will now proceed with the model slightly bigger than the BIC optimal model: \[maxhr \approx age + sex + chestpain + exang + slope + chol + sex*exang + chestpain*slope\] Which has 6 covariates and 2 interaction terms.

3-Way Interaction

Since the model is already complex enough, we will not include 3-way interaction to improve the fit since they are not significantly required.

Diagnostics

First we will check 2 model assumptions - constant variance, and normality.

#Check for constant variance
plot(model.two$fitted.values, model.two$residuals, xlab="Fitted", ylab="Residuals")

#Remove the observations below -40.
plot(model.two$fitted.values, model.two$residuals, xlab="Fitted", ylab="Residuals",
     ylim=c(-40,40))

#Check for normality in errors
qqnorm(residuals(model.two), ylab="Residuals")
qqline(residuals(model.two))

Some observations have extremely (negatively small) residuals, but otherwise, observe that the variance is rather constant, and well distributed. Note that there seem to be 2 clusters, splitting at fitted value = 140, but since the cluster is not very distinguished, we will just keep in view for now.

Observe that the residuals are fairly normal, at least from the -1.5 to 2nd quantile. It may be slightly heavy-tailed.

Let us also plot the residuals against the continuous covariate, to ensure there is constant variance, and no need to transform any variables.

plot(heart$age, model.two$residuals, xlab="AGE", ylab="Residuals")

plot(heart$chol, model.two$residuals, xlab="CHOL", ylab="Residuals")

Notice that there may be a small likelihood of increasing variance in errors as age increases. For Chol, it seems to be normally distributed, but have a few leverage points and points with large negative residuals.

To resolve this, we will complete additional diagnostics test, to indentify any leverage, outliers, and influential points.

Leverage Points

hii <- influence(model.two)$hat
plot(hii, cex=2, col="green", main="Leverage Points")
with(heart, text(hii, font=8))

The leverage points are 17, 290, 1, 28, 184.

Outliers

Define \(X_{(i)}\) as having removed the i-th observation, and \(y_{(i)}\) as the corresponding response value. Recall that \[t_i = \frac{y_i-\hat{y_{(i)}}}{\hat{\sigma^2_{(i)}(1+x_i^T(X_{(i)}^TX_{(i)})^{-1}x_i)^{1/2}}} \sim t_{n-p-1}\] Here, n = 303, n-p-1 = 286. Based on the Bonferroni Correction, we reject the null hypothesis if the critical value > 3.818 

qt(0.05/(303*2), 286)
## [1] -3.818
jack <- abs(rstudent(model.two))

#There is no observations with values > 3.8. Hence, we will find the top 5 observations.
jack[jack>2.5]
##   115   138   245   246 
## 2.939 2.691 3.247 3.409

Influential Points

halfnorm(cooks.distance(model.two), 10,
         main="Cook statistics")

Influential points = 28, 138, 299, 200, 187, 1, 245, 234

To verify this claim, let us plot the effects of removing an i-th observation on the change in the estimated coefficients for the 5 variables.

influence1 <- influence(model.two)
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(influence1$coef[,2],
     ylab=expression(paste("Change in beta_age")))
with(heart, text(heart$age, font=8))

     ylab=expression(paste("Change in beta_sex")))
plot(influence1$coef[,4],
     ylab=expression(paste("Change in beta_exang")))

     ylab=expression(paste("Change in beta_sex:exang")))

Based on the results, let us remove the significant influential points, and regress the model on the new dataset again. 

remove = c(115, 245, 246, 200, 60, 28, 138, 299, 187)
heart.new = heart[-remove,]

model.two.a = lm(maxhr ~ age + sex + chestpain + exang + slope + 
                    sex:exang + chestpain:slope, data = heart.new)


#Check the model assumptions again

Indeed, observe that improvements were made to both the normality QQ plot and the fitted-variance plot, becoming closer to the assumptions.

Huber Regression

Another method for robust regression is to use the Huber regression method. Here, instead of minimizing the square of the differences between predicted and actual value, we will minimize the absolute value of the differences once the difference is above a certain value.

model.three = rlm(maxhr ~ age + sex + chestpain + exang + slope + chol +
                    sex:exang + chestpain:slope, data=heart, maxit=100)

Ridge Regression

Since the core of the question is about predicting maxhr based on the given covariates, we should recognize there exists a variance-bias tradeoff, given that we do NOT know that range of covariates that we will be predicting against. Hence, we should utilize Ridge regression to introduce some bias, in order to reduce the variance of future predictions.

Since only age and chol are continuous functions which have roughly the same magnitude for \(\hat{\beta}\), and the rest are categorical, there will be no need to standardize the covariates. We will use the covariates that have been selected, under Model Two.

The function we are minimizing is \[argmin ||Y - X\hat{\beta}||^2 + \lambda ||\hat{\beta}||^2\]

First, we need to tune our hyperparameter, \(\lambda\). We will do so by Leave-One-Out Cross Validation, and choose the \(\lambda\) that gives us the lowest risk score.

#Set up data matrix for Ridge Regression prediction
heart2 = matrix(0, ncol=17, nrow=303)
heart2[, 1] = 1
heart2[, 2] = heart$age
heart2[, 3] = heart$sex
for (i in 1:303) {
  if (heart$chestpain[i] == 2) {heart2[i, 4] = 1}
  if (heart$chestpain[i] == 3) {heart2[i, 5] = 1}
  if (heart$chestpain[i] == 4) {heart2[i, 6] = 1}
}
heart2[, 7] = heart$exang
for (i in 1:303) {
  if (heart$slope[i] == 2) {heart2[i, 8] = 1}
  if (heart$slope[i] == 3) {heart2[i, 9] = 1}
}
heart2[, 10] = heart2[, 3] * heart2[, 7]
heart2[, 11] = heart2[, 4] * heart2[, 8]
heart2[, 12] = heart2[, 5] * heart2[, 8]
heart2[, 13] = heart2[, 6] * heart2[, 8]
heart2[, 14] = heart2[, 4] * heart2[, 9]
heart2[, 15] = heart2[, 5] * heart2[, 9]
heart2[, 16] = heart2[, 6] * heart2[, 9]
heart2[, 17] = heart$chol


lam.mat = seq(0,10, length=100)
error.mat = rep(0, 100)
for (i in 1:length(lam.mat)) {
  error.sum = 0
  for (j in 1:303) {
    model = lm.ridge(heart$maxhr[-j] ~ heart$age[-j]+heart$sex[-j]+heart$chestpain[-j]+
                       heart$exang[-j]+heart$slope[-j] + (heart$sex[-j])*(heart$exang[-j]) +
                       heart$chestpain[-j]*heart$slope[-j] + heart$chol[-j], lambda = lam.mat[i])
    y.pred = heart2[j,] %*% coef(model)
diff.2 = (y.pred - heart[j,13])^2
error.sum = error.sum + diff.2
}
error = error.sum/303
error.mat[i] = error
}
plot(lam.mat, error.mat, type="l", main="Plot of CV score against Lambda")

index = which.min(error.mat)
opt.lam = lam.mat[index]
opt.lam
## [1] 1.616

Finally, given that we have chosen the bandwidth parameter, let’s run the regression to find out about our final model!

model.opt.ridge = lm.ridge(heart$maxhr ~ heart$age+heart$sex+heart$chestpain+
                       heart$exang+heart$slope + (heart$sex)*(heart$exang) +
                       heart$chestpain*heart$slope + heart$chol, lambda = opt.lam)

Analysis

From above, we have obtained 3 models, model.two (from model selection process), model.three (robust regression process), and model.opt.ridge (from ridge regression process).

If we are suppose to predict a new observation that has covariates not in the range of the heart data, then we should use the model obtained from Ridge Regression, given that it introduces some biases to lower overall variance, ensuring that the model will neither overfit our existing data, nor underfit new data.

Otherwise, we should consider the model obtained from Huber regression. Note that the Huber model behaves like LS regression for small residuals, but if the residuals is large, it behaves like LAD regression. This is because when we perform diagnostics for the selected model, we noticed some problems, and detected some influential points and outliers. Hence, since Huber is a robust regression method, it prevents final results from being overwhelmingly affected by outliers.

Level of Significance

Since all 3 models are roughly similar in the sign of each coefficient, and only differs in magnitude, I will proceed with interpreting the main model, model.two, which the latter 2 models are built on.

First, notice that only 5 coefficients have p-values of < 0.10 in the t-test. Then, why are other covariates included? This is because the 5 are:

  1. Intercept

  2. age

  3. chol

  4. sex:exang

  5. chestpain(4):slope(2)

Since it is unnatural to include interaction terms if the variables are not included in the model, we included them all, since accordingly to the F-test, the bigger model will be preferred even if the one-way covariates are not significant. Moreover, if we want to include a level of the categorical variable, we have to include all the levels.

Interpretation

  • The intercept is 191.57. This implies that if a person is just born, female, and has no issues in other categories, then the maxhr = 191.57. This is on the high side, but fair considering that age 0 is outside the age range of data - hence, some extrapolation and distance from the means cause this error.

  • Next, coefficient for age is negative. Hence, the older a person is, the lower his/her maxhr will be, controlled for other variables. This makes logical sense.

  • A male is expected to have a maxhr of 1.5049 more compared to a female, other factors controlled. This is insignificantly small, but is understandable since the p-value is large too. More likely sex only plays a big role in interaction.

  • When controlled for other factors, a person with the largest maxhr is likely to be one with chestpain2, followed by chestpain4, then chestpain1, finally chestpain3 has the smallest maxhr.

  • If a female person has exercise-induced angina, she is likely to have a higher maxhr of 3.2643 than another female, when other variables are controlled.

  • If the person is male, then this difference changes by (3.2643 - 14.8661) - interestingly, when controlled for other factors besides exang and sex, exang has an opposite effect on males, it gives them a lower maxhr.

  • Similarly, a person with slope2’s ECG change will have a slightly higher maxhr than slope1. Yet, slope3 will have a large decrease in maxhr than slope1.

  • There are also interactions between chestpain and slope. If a person has slope2 AND chestpain, then his/her maxhr will decrease rather significantly. On the reverse, if a person has Slope3 AND chestpain (but only of type 2 and 3), then his maxhr will increase by almost 20. This accounts for why slope3 has a negative (but large in magnitude) coefficient; it will be cancelled out if a persona has chestpain 2 or 3. Hence, slope2 and slope3 interacts with chestpain rather differently, in opposite direction in fact.

  • When controlled for other variables, an increase in chol by 1 leads to an increase in Maxhr by 0.0416.

To conclude:

In our final model, we include 6 variables (age, sex, chestpain, exang, slope, chol) and 2 interactions (sex:exang, chestpain:slope). To account for outliers and the usage of the model (predictive nature), we also utilize Robust Regression (Huber) and Ridge Regression to introduce variants of the model.
